Gerard,

The CPU time is nonlinear in problem size since the governing equations 
for all reactors in a network are integrated together using an implicit 
algorithm (backward differencing with a full, numerically-computed 
Jacobian). The Jacobian size scales with (number of reactors)^2. This 
is required to correctly handle the couplings between reactors.

If the reactors can be grouped into subnetworks that are weakly 
coupled, it may be possible to put each subnetwork in a separate 
ReactorNet object, and loop over the set of subnetworks, advancing each 
one through a small timestep.  Not that any couplings between reactors 
in different subnetworks would only be evaluated  for the fixed reactor 
conditions of that timestep, so you would have to make the timestep 
small enough to resolve these couplings.

The Reactor and ReactorNet objects may not be optimal for your 
application. They were not written with the idea of using them within 
CFD codes.  If they work for your application, that&#39;s great, but if 
they are too slow you might want to write the solver or integrator for 
the relevant system of equations yourself, and use Cantera just to 
evaluate thermo properties and reaction rates in your equations.

Dave



